# Variable Naming

## Rule

Use **full-word, descriptive names** for variables, parameters, and bindings. **Do not** use single-letter identifiers (`x`, `e`, `n`, `t`, `k`, `v`, etc.) except where a language or API **requires** a specific name or an **exception** below applies.

`i` and `j` are **not** covered by this rule when used **only** as loop counters (see **Loop indices**).

## Rationale

Single-letter names hide intent, complicate review, and age poorly when logic grows. Descriptive names document the code with minimal extra effort. Traditional index names `i` / `j` in loops are a narrow, readable exception.

## Examples

### ❌ Avoid

```typescript
const n = items.length;
const t = items[0];
process(t);

items.map((x) => transform(x));

function onClick(e: MouseEvent) {
  e.preventDefault();
}
```

### ✅ Prefer (general)

```typescript
const itemCount = items.length;
const first = items[0];
process(first);

items.map((item) => transform(item));

function onClick(event: MouseEvent) {
  event.preventDefault();
}
```

### ✅ Allowed — loop indices `i` and `j`

Use `i` and `j` for numeric loop counters, including nested loops:

```typescript
for (let i = 0; i < rows.length; i++) {
  for (let j = 0; j < rows[i].length; j++) {
    process(rows[i][j]);
  }
}

let i = 0;
while (i < items.length) {
  process(items[i]);
  i++;
}

items.map((item, i) => transform(item, i));
```

The same applies to the **numeric index parameter** in `.map` / `.filter` / `.forEach` (and similar) when it is clearly an index: use `i`, or `j` in an inner callback when comparing to an outer row index `i`.

Do **not** reuse `i` / `j` for non-index meanings (e.g. storing a user id or event); use a full-word name there.

## Scope

Applies to **new and edited** code: locals, function parameters, destructuring aliases, catch bindings (`error` not `err` unless matching an external convention), and inline callbacks.

## Exceptions

- **Loop indices**: `i` and `j` as the index variable in `for` / `while` loops (including nested loops: outer `i`, inner `j` is conventional), and as the index argument in array callbacks (`map`, `filter`, `forEach`, etc.) when it denotes a position.
- **Required by API**: e.g. a library callback signature that must be named a certain way (still prefer wrapping with a descriptive local if it improves clarity).
- **Mathematical domains** where symbols are universal: use sparingly and only when the symbol is the domain standard (e.g. coordinates in a tight geometric helper may use `x`/`y` if documented).

When in doubt, spell it out.
